    <text>
        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Sept and Oct 1889<lb/></p>
            <p>Three letters to the Secretary<lb/> of the Alliance &#40;in French&#41;&#45;&#45;Addressed to Monsieur Loeb&#45;&#45;&#42; Asking first<lb/> that those colonists who cannot<lb/> pay the interest on the money<lb/> loaned them be allowed to<lb/> defer payment&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Then he asks for money 40 or 50<lb/> thousand dollars&#45;&#45;for a building<lb/> on Lombard&#44; South&#44; or Bainbridge<lb/> Street&#45;&#45;for The Russians&#45;&#45;<lb/> &#34;I have preached this need<lb/> every where for a year&#45;&#45;a building<lb/> with a school&#45;&#45;a kindergarten&#45;&#45;<lb/>a trade school&#45;&#45;english instruction<lb/> a small chapel to attract the<lb/> young people who unfortunately<lb/> see religious services that<lb/> are a disgrace to religion<lb/></p>
                
            <p>dated	Sept 8&#44; 1889<lb/>
                Oct 23&#44; 1889<lb/>
                Oct 28&#44; 1889<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>They have promised me<lb/> little sums&#45;&#45;your influence<lb/> with M. le Baron&#45;&#45;In the facade<lb/> of this building the name of the<lb/> great Philanthropist would be<lb/> carved in ineffaceable characters<lb/></p>
            <p>II The Russians who have been here<lb/> 6 or 7 years have given us<lb/> much trouble.  I approached<lb/> them with friendship and I<lb/> preached to them the law of<lb/> honesty and of work with<lb/> brotherly feeling&#45;&#45;but unfortunately<lb/> my words did not succeed as well<lb/> as I hoped.  However I wish<lb/> to save their children from<lb/> the two evils which threaten them<lb/> bigotry or nihilism<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>In the kindergarten they will<lb/> learn cleanliness and the habits<lb/> of civilized people&#45;&#45;and we<lb/> will give them whatever clothes<lb/> they need and lunch.<lb/></p>
            <p>There are many children 7 or 8<lb/> who go to public school&#45;&#45;but<lb/> there <sic>ar</sic> also many who sell<lb/> <sic>matchs</sic> or lemons in the street<lb/> and who are exposed evil<lb/> influences.  To deliver them we<lb/> think of starting a trade school<lb/> teaching English and writing in the<lb/> evening.  We have already tried<lb/> that but in a very limited<lb/> group.<lb/></p>
            <p>The land would cost &#36;15&#44;000 the<lb/> building &#36;20&#44;000&#45;&#45;3 stories not<lb/> wanting a large basement<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>workshop in the basement&#45;&#45;on the<lb/> other floors&#45;&#45;schoolrooms&#45;&#45;a<lb/> library&#45;&#45;lecture rooms&#45;&#45;a little<lb/> synagogue.  There are unfortunately<lb/> too many schules among The Russians<lb/> for they stay among themselves<lb/> although there are a few in my<lb/> synagogue and I encourage<lb/> them to come there&#45;&#45;But I wish<lb/> to have a room in this same<lb/> building in which on Saturday<lb/> afternoon or evening religious<lb/> services can be held which will<lb/> give the young Russians an idea<lb/> of the dignity of prayer&#45;&#45;and<lb/> to have lectures not in jargon<lb/> but in the language of the country<lb/></p>
            <p>5. Once the building is built I am<lb/> almost sure that we could obtain<lb/> the means to maintain it by<lb/> strict economy<lb/></p>
            <p>We will also have a sewing schoolrooms<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="5"/>
            <p>I was in a school for children<lb/> to&#45;day and discovered that<lb/> unfortunately the kindergarten<lb/> had been forced to close for<lb/> lack of funds.<lb/></p>
            <p>I enclose a memorandum which<lb/> will give you an idea of what<lb/> is being done in New York<lb/> for the education of the<lb/> Russians.  I go there often<lb/> because of a Theological<lb/> Seminary and I find there<lb/> an indescribable enthusiasm<lb/></p>
            </body>
